description: About 4-6 dead fish just lying dead about 7 feet away from the shore. They were way to far from where the water would be at high tide. All but one were in good condition and the only thing that looked wrong with the was the early stages of decay and what the flies were starting to get. No visible signs of disease and none looked like they were prey either.

Definitely an example of this species and multiple species. This was one of the largest of the carp species shown. There may have been other species but I tried to focus for the moment on the carp before the camera batteries ran out. I am assuming this is a dumpster for the disposal of the invasive species (focusing of course on the silver carp). The smell was impressive but the carp were not all over the bank just in the dumpster.

Asian Silver Carp

This is an aggressive, exotic, invasive species which is now unfortunately becoming common in the Mississippi River ecosystem.   See news report at: 
http://on.aol.com/video/asian-carp-invade-mississippi-waterways-517843727

We were taking an afternoon outing on the MS river with 5 of us in an outboard motor boat in a backwater, when carp started jumping nearby. They have *incredible* musculature and can leap up to 5ft out of the water. Suddenly TWO of them jumped up and landed right IN our boat. Amazingly neither of these 4-5 lb'ers struck one of us! See photos attached.
